## Step 4: Disassemble `test` — understand the key derivation

```
(gdb) disas test
```

Key instructions:

```asm
804874d: mov    0x8(%ebp),%eax       ← load a (user input)
8048750: mov    0xc(%ebp),%edx       ← load b (0x1337d00d)
8048755: sub    %eax,%ecx            ← d = b - a
804875c: cmpl   $0x15,-0xc(%ebp)     ← if d > 21...
8048760: ja     804884a              ← ...jump to default (rand path)
```

If `d <= 21`, a **jump table** at `0x80489f0` is used:

```asm
8048766: mov    -0xc(%ebp),%eax      ← load d
8048769: shl    $0x2,%eax            ← d * 4 (dword index)
804876c: add    $0x80489f0,%eax      ← jump_table[d]
8048773: jmp    *%eax                ← indirect jump
```

We can inspect the jump table in GDB:

```
(gdb) x/22xw 0x80489f0
```

All 22 entries (cases 0–21) lead to the same pattern: `decrypt(d)`.
The default path calls `decrypt(rand())` — uncontrollable.

So: **key = 0x1337d00d − input**, and key must be between 0 and 21.

---

## Step 5: Disassemble `decrypt` — find the encrypted buffer and target string

```
(gdb) disas decrypt
```

### The encrypted buffer (built on the stack)

```asm
0x08048673 <+19>:    movl   $0x757c7d51,-0x1d(%ebp)
0x0804867a <+26>:    movl   $0x67667360,-0x19(%ebp)
0x08048681 <+33>:    movl   $0x7b66737e,-0x15(%ebp)
0x08048688 <+40>:    movl   $0x33617c7d,-0x11(%ebp)
0x0804868f <+47>:    movb   $0x0,-0xd(%ebp)             ← NUL terminator
```

In memory order (little-endian dwords): `51 7d 7c 75 60 73 66 67 7e 73 66 7b 7d 7c 61 33 00`

We can verify in GDB by setting a breakpoint inside `decrypt`:

```
(gdb) b *0x0804869c                                      ← after buffer is built
(gdb) run
Password:0
(gdb) x/17bx $ebp-0x1d
0x...: 0x51 0x7d 0x7c 0x75 0x60 0x73 0x66 0x67
0x...: 0x7e 0x73 0x66 0x7b 0x7d 0x7c 0x61 0x33 0x00
```

### The XOR decryption loop

```asm
0x080486cd <+109>:   movzbl (%eax),%eax               ← load buffer[i]
0x080486d5 <+117>:   xor    %edx,%eax                 ← XOR with key (arg at 0x8(%ebp))
0x080486df <+127>:   mov    %dl,(%eax)                 ← store back
0x080486e1 <+129>:   addl   $0x1,-0x28(%ebp)           ← i++
0x080486eb <+139>:   jb     0x80486c7                  ← loop while i < len
```

Equivalent C: `for (i = 0; i < 16; i++) buffer[i] ^= key;`

### The comparison target

```asm
0x080486f2 <+146>:   mov    $0x80489c3,%eax            ← address of expected string
0x080486f7 <+151>:   mov    $0x11,%ecx                 ← compare 17 bytes (16 + NUL)
0x08048700 <+160>:   repz cmpsb                        ← strncmp-style compare
```

We read the target string:

```
(gdb) x/s 0x80489c3
0x80489c3: "Congratulations!"
```

And the success/failure paths:

```
(gdb) x/s 0x80489d4
0x80489d4: "/bin/sh"                                    ← system() argument on match
(gdb) x/s 0x80489dc
0x80489dc: "Nope"                                       ← puts() on mismatch
```

